<H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Lesson 2 - Copyright 1:</FONT></H3>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Copyright In Cyberspace</FONT></H1></CENTER>
Consider the following situations:<P>
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI>You buy a piece of software and e-mail it to five friends.<P>
<LI>You download an article from a newspaper's Web page and post in on an electronic bulletin board.<P>
<LI>You take a post from one news group and forward it to another news group.<P>
<LI>You respond to someone's discussion list post, and quote part of his post in yours</UL>.
Each of these examples implicates copyright law.  In each of them there's at least a possibility that you'd be violating the law (though we'll find that in at least some of them you're probably safe).<P>
Copyright law<P>
<OL>
<LI>usually<P>
<LI>gives a copyright owner the exclusive right to control      copying<P>
<LI>of a writing (or recording or picture or electronic      transcription).<P>
</OL>
In the next several messages, we'll explore each of these three elements.<P>
<B>A WORD OF WARNING:</B>  Copyright law can be maddeningly vague, and copyright law online is doubly vague.  We&#180;ll often say something &quot;might&quot;be legal, and you might often be frustrated by it.  But we have to be honest here - though copyright law is certain in some areas, it&#180;s uncertain in others.<P>
Under these circumstances, &quot;might makes right&quot;.<P>

